{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491623","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491623"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:55:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:55:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1001"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1001","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1001"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.23,0.09,0.06,0.53]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1001"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106199"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1001","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1001"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1001"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88667"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1154"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"1308"},{"type":"tags","id":"2157"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2174"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2295"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39099"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106199","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106199"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 38-year-old woman presents with a two-day history of pain and redness in her right eye, associated with photophobia. On examination she has a visual acuity of 6/12 in the right eye and 6/6 in the left eye. Intraocular pressures are normal. Slit lamp examination shows the presence of cells and flare in the anterior chamber. Dilated fundus examination is normal. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial topical treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pilocarpine","Chloramphenicol","Acetazolamide","Timolol","Topical dexamethasone"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical picture is consistent with acute anterior uveitis. Anterior uveitis involves inflammation of the iris and the ciliary body. Treatment involves \u003Cstrong\u003Etopical steroid\u003C/strong\u003E to address the inflammation and a dilating drop (e.g. cyclopentolate) to help reduce the pain from spasm of the pupillary constrictor and ciliary muscles and prevent posterior synechiae development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPilocarpine is a muscarinic agonist which constricts the pupil and can help open up the trabecular meshwork to reduce intraocular pressure. This is not required in this patient. Chloramphenicol is an antibiotic used to treat bacterial conjunctivitis. Acetazolamide is a carbonic anhydrase inhibitor which decreases production of aqueous humor and is used to treat high intraocular pressures. Timolol is a beta-blocker also used to treat high intraocular pressure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A topical steroid should be administered in cases of suspected acute anterior uveitis."],"references":["Bowling, B. (2015). Kanski\u2019s clinical ophthalmology (8th ed.). W B Saunders.","Duplechain A, Conrady CD, Patel BC, et al. Uveitis. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK540993/","Agrawal RV, Murthy S, Sangwan V, Biswas J. Current approach in diagnosis and management of anterior uveitis. Indian J Ophthalmol. 2010 Jan-Feb;58(1):11-9. doi: 10.4103/0301-4738.58468. PMID: 20029142; PMCID: PMC2841369. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC2841369/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88667"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1001"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88667","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88667"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-16T19:11:58+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-16T19:24:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1001"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106199"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"d